<span id="freeTextContainer6706876138314428731">I read the first half of this book after year 1 or 2 of marriage. We received it as anniversary gift from a wonderful college professor. I liked it, but it fell to the bottom of my reading list for a while. I just finished the second half in year 5 of marriage and WOW. It is one of the most beautifully written, honest books on marriage I’ve read. His reflections are profound. This book is much deeper than other books in the marriage genre. Perhaps because his writing is more personal. It feels l</span>
  <span id="freeText6706876138314428731" style="display:none">I read the first half of this book after year 1 or 2 of marriage. We received it as anniversary gift from a wonderful college professor. I liked it, but it fell to the bottom of my reading list for a while. I just finished the second half in year 5 of marriage and WOW. It is one of the most beautifully written, honest books on marriage I’ve read. His reflections are profound. This book is much deeper than other books in the marriage genre. Perhaps because his writing is more personal. It feels like a conversation with a really wise, honest mentor rather than a preachy, “here’s how to do better” approach. I underlined a ton and gained deeper insights about the Gospel as well. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6706876138314428731" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

