<div id="review_4536484077" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4536484077" />
    <a title="Thomas Ackerman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/87165919-thomas-ackerman"><img alt="Thomas Ackerman" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4536484077?book_show_action=true">Feb 07, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Thomas Ackerman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Thomas Ackerman" href="/user/show/87165919-thomas-ackerman">Thomas Ackerman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/18921141-the-mystery-of-marriage">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4536484077" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer993065539996121352">I find this book a combination of material that is soft on content, containing little strong biblical doctrine, and material that is just false, or so distorted as to qualify as false. Much of the book can be described as trying to make marriage sound more novel and exciting, with little grounding in the Bible. It tries to make good traditional conception of marriage sound not flashy enough, and bring some of the writer&apos;s own wow and jazz to marriage to make it sound more exciting. It tries to b</span>
  <span id="freeText993065539996121352" style="display:none">I find this book a combination of material that is soft on content, containing little strong biblical doctrine, and material that is just false, or so distorted as to qualify as false. Much of the book can be described as trying to make marriage sound more novel and exciting, with little grounding in the Bible. It tries to make good traditional conception of marriage sound not flashy enough, and bring some of the writer's own wow and jazz to marriage to make it sound more exciting. It tries to be novel, and basically tries to jazz it up. While not always false, it has little nutrition, and can be misleading being rooted so heavily in the writer's thoughts and opinions. It also lacked much solid practical advice for the married. <br /><br />At worst, this book is feminized false doctrine. In a section on submission, it completely ignores biblical headship and submission -- which are the real authority of the husband and obedience of the wife -- for the hammered flat definition of simply being considerate and caring for the other's needs. There's nothing wrong with being considerate and caring, but there is something wrong with making it sound like that is what biblical submission is. <br /><br />Nearly every usage of the word submit in the New Testament refers to submitting to a higher authority, or being controlled by a more powerful force. Similar words in Hebrew in the Old Testament also overwhelmingly mean the same. Submission is putting yourself under the authority of another, and obeying him, which is what the wife does towards her husband, and NOT the other way around. A husband is never taught to submit to his wife. Rather he is the head, which like Christ and like the Father, is the leadership position, which moves the body. Similarly the common word for obey is used to describe how the godly wife acts toward her husband, being used side by side with submit in 1 Peter 3. Biblical headship and submission is no ambiguous doctrine. <br /><br />While the author briefly mentions the teaching of Ephesians 5 for the wife to submit to her husband, he only does so for the sake of quickly dismissing it for the primacy of his mutual "submission." This is false teaching, and is intellectually dishonest. Biblical headship and submission represents a vertical authority structure, as it does with masters and servants, parents and children, governments and citizens, God and mankind, using the exact same language it does when speaking of husband and wife. <br /><br />Therefore, my advice is to ignore a book like this, which is too tainted by contemporary views of marriage and of gender, and not actually motivated by the Bible's teachings, and which moreover is mostly the personal musings of the author.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="993065539996121352" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


