              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16609361931246732564">Mike Mason&apos;s book on marriage is beautiful, unique, and often quite profound. There was a lot I loved about it. On the other hand, I think I&apos;m just too tired to take in page after page of language so flowry and poetic. It was, at times, a little over the top. I think it would be better digested in a different format - like 200 1-page essays instead of 8 traditional chapters. A devotional, maybe? <br/><br/>Anyway, the subject matter was good. I especially liked the chapters Vow and Submission. I ended the </span>
  <span id="freeText16609361931246732564" style="display:none">Mike Mason's book on marriage is beautiful, unique, and often quite profound. There was a lot I loved about it. On the other hand, I think I'm just too tired to take in page after page of language so flowry and poetic. It was, at times, a little over the top. I think it would be better digested in a different format - like 200 1-page essays instead of 8 traditional chapters. A devotional, maybe? <br /><br />Anyway, the subject matter was good. I especially liked the chapters Vow and Submission. I ended the book thankful to have chosen my man and forsaken all others, to be married to someone who embraces the concept of "one-downsmanship" (151) and loves me to the full extent of the word. I loved the section on being perfect for one another - the idea that neither spouse needs to be perfect to be perfect for each other - it is a relational perfection instead of a functional one (178).<br /><br />Perhaps I will revisit at some point in the future, with plans to read only one page per sitting. </span>
